"{\"uid\": \"standard.co.uk-sport-sport-olympics-max-whitlock-retirement-paris-olympics-2024-b1150506.html\", \"text\": \"To use the search feature, we need your consent to load Google Custom Search, which may use cookies or similar technologies. Please click 'Allow and Continue' below to enable search. See our privacy policy for more information.  Sport|Olympics  Max Whitlockwill retire following theParis Olympics, he announced on Wednesday morning.  Whitlock is a three-time Olympic champion and boasts six medals spanning three Games dating back to London 2012.  And he has set his sights on a golden Games farewell in the French capital this summer on the pommel horse, his No1 apparatus.  \\\"The decision now feels right,\\\" Whitlock told BBC Breakfast. \\\"Going for my final Olympic Games, it feels very, very strange talking about it, and it's almost hard to articulate what it's like.  \\\"It's a really nice mindset to be in, to think I will just give it all I have got. Ever since Rio where I was at my peak age, I think I have had questions thrown at me about when am I retiring.  \\\"I have wanted to prove people wrong a lot of the way through my journey and I have always had the mindset of trying to do this for as long as I possibly can.  \\\"Now, I have given myself the opportunity for Willow [his daughter] to come and watch an Olympic Games because she could not in Tokyo. That's such a good feeling for me.  \\\"When I am in areas competing, Willow waits for it to go quiet and she calls for me, and we do this double thumbs-up. I think I'd love to do that in the Paris Olympics.\\\"  MORE ABOUT  Have your say...  1  Crime  Fight breaks out on Elizabeth line train after youths told to stop vaping by middle-aged passenger  Fight breaks out on Elizabeth line after youths told to stop vaping  2  Football  Liverpool XI vs Brighton: Starting lineup, confirmed team news, injury latest for Premier League today  Liverpool XI vs Brighton: Starting lineup and confirmed team 